    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a compact summary containing: total row count, minimum timestamp, maximum timestamp, list of unique cmdb_id values, and the top 20 most frequent names in that file with their counts (for metric.csv use kpi_name, for trace.csv use trace_name, for log.csv use log_name, for error_logs.csv show top 20 messages by frequency). Keep outputs compact and return only these aggregates."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor summary: metric.csv has 29,355 rows from many components (26 unique cmdb_ids) and contains many OS and app KPIs; trace.csv has 7,203 rows across 12 cmdb_ids and includes trace.self.* and trace.to_/from_* features; log.csv has 463 rows across 6 cmdb_ids with log.error_count, log.row_count, log.gc_pause_max; error_logs.csv has 0 rows. The incident window is 2021-03-25 09:00:00 to 2021-03-25 09:30:00 Asia/Shanghai (epoch 1616634000 to 1616635800). Given the abundance of metric data and sparse logs/errors, metrics analysis should be used first to narrow candidates. No fault has been identified yet. Next step: calculate global thresholds for each component-KPI using the full available series (before filtering), then identify anomalies in the incident window by comparing window values to those global thresholds. Store intermediate tables in kernel variables for later trace/log correlation. ",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv do the following and keep intermediate tables in kernel variables (do not print full time series):\n1) Aggregate the full metric series (no time filtering) by cmdb_id and kpi_name and compute for each group: series_count, global_p95, global_p90, global_p5, series_min, series_max. \n2) Filter metric.csv to timestamps between 1616634000 and 1616635800 inclusive (the incident window). For each component-KPI group in this window compute: window_count, anomaly_count_p95 (number of points with value > global_p95), earliest_anom_ts_p95 (the earliest timestamp in the window where value > global_p95, or null), max_in_window, mean_in_window.\n3) Return a compact table of at most top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count_p95 descending showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, series_count, global_p95, global_p90, global_p5, window_count, anomaly_count_p95, earliest_anom_ts_p95, max_in_window, mean_in_window.\n4) Also return a small list of unique cmdb_id values that have anomaly_count_p95 > 0 with the count of distinct anomalous KPIs per cmdb_id (limit to top 20 cmdb_id entries)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric analysis step (global thresholds computed on full metric series, then filtered to the incident window) found many component-KPI groups with anomalies (value > global P95) during 2021-03-25 09:00–09:30 CST. Top components by anomalous KPIs/points include Mysql02, Mysql01, Tomcat01, MG01, Tomcat04, MG02, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, IG01, IG02, Redis01, Redis02, apache01, apache02. Example anomalous KPIs include large JVM heap usage spikes (IG01/IG02/MG01/MG02), many OS and app KPIs, and app.cnt/app.mrt spikes for some ServiceTest entries. This narrows the candidates but does not yet identify the single root cause component or exact occurrence time. According to the diagnosis workflow, we must now use traces to disambiguate among multiple service-level faulty components (traces can point to the most downstream faulty service in call chains) and to confirm timing. Trace analysis should use global thresholds computed from the full trace series (not filtered) and then detect anomalies in the incident window: for duration metrics detect points > global P95; for row_count detect significant drops (<= global P5). We should return compact aggregates (counts, earliest anomaly timestamp) and map which trace anomalies involve the metric-anomalous components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv perform: 1) Compute global thresholds (full series) grouped by cmdb_id and trace_name: series_count, global_p95, global_p5. 2) Filter trace rows to the incident window timestamps 1616634000..1616635800 inclusive. For each group in the window compute: window_count, anomaly_count_duration (for trace names containing 'duration' count points with value > global_p95), anomaly_count_rowcount (for trace names containing 'row_count' count points with value <= global_p5), earliest_anom_ts (earliest timestamp among any anomaly types in window or null), max_in_window, mean_in_window. 3) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) sorted by total anomaly count (anomaly_count_duration + anomaly_count_rowcount) descending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, series_count, global_p95, global_p5, window_count, anomaly_count_duration, anomaly_count_rowcount, earliest_anom_ts, max_in_window, mean_in_window. 4) Also return a small list of cmdb_id values that appear both in the metric-anomalous-components list and in the trace-anomaly results, with counts of distinct anomalous trace_names per cmdb_id (limit top 20)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection across metrics, traces, and logs for the incident window (2021-03-25 09:00–09:30 CST). Summary of findings so far:\n- Metrics: widespread anomalies (>global P95) across many components (Mysql01/02, Tomcat01..04, MG01/02, IG01/02, Redis01/02, apache01/02). IG and MG nodes showed JVM heap spikes earliest around 09:05–09:08. Tomcats show many KPI anomalies with earliest timestamps at ~09:00–09:02 and anomalies spanning the whole window.\n- Traces: a concentrated duration (latency) anomaly cluster is visible at 2021-03-25 09:13:00 CST involving IG (trace.self.duration_* and trace.to_Tomcat*.duration_*). Several IG->Tomcat traces have duration anomalies with earliest trace-duration anomalies at 09:13.\n- Logs: Tomcat and apache log.row_count drops; notably Tomcat01 log.row_count earliest anomaly is 09:13:00 CST, while Tomcat02/03/04 and apache row_count anomalies are earlier (~09:05). GC pause spikes exist for Tomcat04 (~09:02) and others at later times. error_logs.csv is empty.\nReasoning to this point: The observed single failure likely manifested as the trace-duration spike at 09:13. According to the rules, when multiple service-level faulty components are identified, the root cause component is typically the most downstream faulty service within the trace call chain. Trace anomalies at 09:13 implicate IG->Tomcat calls. Tomcat01 has a matching log.row_count drop at 09:13, making it a candidate; however, Tomcat01 metric KPI anomalies mostly began earlier (09:00–09:06) and none were found that first appear exactly at 09:13. IG01 trace-duration anomalies do start at 09:13 (trace.self.duration_* and trace.to_Tomcat*), so IG01 itself may have been experiencing latency at 09:13 and is a plausible root cause candidate. We still lack confirmation of the underlying resource reason (e.g., high CPU, high memory/JVM, GC, disk) for the 09:13 failure. To disambiguate whether IG01 (service-level latency) or Tomcat01 (downstream drop) is the true root cause and to identify the resource reason, we must inspect IG01’s metric KPIs around 09:13 for anomalies and severity (how far they breached thresholds).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For IG01 only: from metric.csv (use full-series global thresholds before window filtering) compute and return a compact report limited to top 20 rows of IG01 component-KPI groups where anomaly_count_p95 > 0 in the incident window (1616634000..1616635800). For each row return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, series_count, global_p95, window_count, anomaly_count_p95, earliest_anom_ts_p95_local, max_in_window, mean_in_window, severity_ratio = max_in_window / global_p95 (null if global_p95 == 0). Sort rows by earliest_anom_ts_p95_local ascending then severity_ratio descending. Also return a small list of KPI groups from this result whose earliest_anom_ts_p95_local == '2021-03-25 09:13:00 CST' (list kpi_name and severity_ratio). Finally return an IG01 aggregate row with: cmdb_id, distinct_anomalous_kpi_count, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_ts_local across all IG01 KPIs. Keep outputs compact and limit rows to 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the prior Executor results we have: widespread metric anomalies across many components in the incident window, trace-duration anomalies concentrated at 2021-03-25 09:13:00 CST (notably IG01 trace.self.duration_* and IG01->Tomcat* durations), and Tomcat log.row_count drops with Tomcat01 showing a log.row_count anomaly at 09:13:00 CST. IG01 metric anomalies exist (some at 09:13) but metric severity_ratios for IG01 KPIs are only slightly above 1 (small breaches), and Tomcat01 metrics mostly show earliest anomalies earlier than 09:13. According to the diagnosis rules, the root cause for a single failure should be the most downstream faulty service in traces; however, trace-duration anomalies at 09:13 affect IG and IG->Tomcat* calls. To discriminate whether IG01 (service-level latency) or Tomcat01 (downstream) is the root cause, we need to quantify the severity of trace-duration anomalies (how far duration metrics exceeded their global thresholds) and compare severity to metric severity. If trace-duration severity is large (>>50%), it points to a real latency fault at that service layer. Therefore the next step is to compute severity ratios for trace-duration anomalies (max_in_window / global_p95) and present the top trace anomaly rows and the specific IG01 trace rows (trace.self.* and trace.to_Tomcat*), plus any entries involving Tomcat01, with earliest anomaly timestamps. This will let us judge which component shows the most significant deviation at ~09:13 and support root cause localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously computed trace anomaly results (or recompute from trace.csv with full-series global thresholds if needed), compute severity_ratio = max_in_window / global_p95 for each trace group that has anomalies in the incident window. Return: \n1) A compact table (limit 20 rows) sorted by severity_ratio descending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, series_count, global_p95, window_count, anomaly_count_duration, anomaly_count_rowcount, earliest_anom_ts, max_in_window, mean_in_window, severity_ratio. \n2) A focused table (up to 10 rows) filtered to rows where cmdb_id == 'IG01' or trace_name contains 'Tomcat01', showing the same columns sorted by earliest_anom_ts ascending. \n3) A short aggregate list of top 5 cmdb_id by mean severity_ratio among their anomalous trace groups (show cmdb_id and mean_severity_ratio and total_trace_anomaly_points). \nLimit outputs to compact aggregates (no raw time series)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The trace-severity analysis shows the strongest anomalies (largest severity_ratio) concentrated at 2021-03-25 09:13:00 CST and involving dockerA ↔ MG communication paths. MG01 and MG02 appear among the top components by mean trace severity (both with many anomaly points). IG01 and some Tomcats also show anomalies at 09:13, but their trace severity ratios are much smaller (IG01 trace.to_Tomcat01.duration_p95 severity ≈ 1.60) compared with MG-related traces (severity up to ≈3.7). According to the rules, since the root cause component must be chosen from the provided components list and dockerA* entries are not in that list, we should focus on MG01/MG02 (they are present in the allowed component set and show very large trace severity at the failure minute). Metrics show MG JVM/heap spikes earlier (~09:05–09:07) but the most pronounced trace-duration spikes occur at 09:13. We still lack direct evidence of the underlying resource reason on MG01/MG02 (e.g., CPU, memory, JVM OOM, disk, or network) at the exact failure minute. To localize the root cause component and reason for the single failure at ~09:13, we need to inspect MG01 and MG02 metric anomalies (global-P95 based) around the 09:13 minute and quantify severity of their resource KPIs at that time. This will tell us whether MG01 or MG02 experienced a resource-level fault that plausibly caused the high-duration traces at 09:13.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For MG01 and MG02 only: using the metric anomaly results computed with full-series global thresholds, return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of anomalous component-KPI groups where anomaly_count_p95 > 0 within the incident window. For each row include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, series_count, global_p95, window_count, anomaly_count_p95, earliest_anom_ts_p95_local, max_in_window, mean_in_window, severity_ratio = max_in_window / global_p95 (null if global_p95==0). Sort rows by earliest_anom_ts_p95_local ascending, then severity_ratio descending. Also return an aggregate row per component (MG01 and MG02) with: cmdb_id, distinct_anomalous_kpi_count, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_ts_local. Keep outputs compact and limit rows to 20."
}

